WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.148 align:middle line:90%


00:00:05.148 --> 00:00:07.660 align:middle line:84%
>>>>[THEME MUSIC] And I think
many people today don't

00:00:07.660 --> 00:00:08.930 align:middle line:90%
know what to believe anymore.

00:00:08.930 --> 00:00:10.670 align:middle line:84%
>>People are basically
going to keep on

00:00:10.670 --> 00:00:13.290 align:middle line:84%
to help uncover what
really happened.

00:00:13.290 --> 00:00:15.640 align:middle line:84%
>>I felt like something
was watching me.

00:00:15.640 --> 00:00:17.890 align:middle line:84%
>>We weren't given
all the information.

00:00:17.890 --> 00:00:19.610 align:middle line:84%
We weren't told
the entire story.

00:00:19.610 --> 00:00:25.550 align:middle line:90%


00:00:25.550 --> 00:00:26.320 align:middle line:90%
[THEME MUSIC]

00:00:26.320 --> 00:00:28.190 align:middle line:90%


00:00:28.190 --> 00:00:32.209 align:middle line:84%
>>We've heard of your
arrival from many sources.

00:00:32.209 --> 00:00:35.139 align:middle line:90%


00:00:35.139 --> 00:00:36.119 align:middle line:90%
[EXPLOSIVE BURST]

00:00:36.119 --> 00:00:38.569 align:middle line:90%


00:00:38.569 --> 00:00:40.529 align:middle line:90%
[SIRENS]

00:00:40.529 --> 00:00:45.919 align:middle line:90%


00:00:45.919 --> 00:00:48.859 align:middle line:84%
>>I feel something horrible
is going to happen to you.

00:00:48.859 --> 00:00:52.372 align:middle line:84%
>>This proposal is
quite extraordinary.

00:00:52.372 --> 00:00:54.370 align:middle line:84%
>>Capital City's
president is considering

00:00:54.370 --> 00:00:57.050 align:middle line:84%
signing an agreement with
them for their technology.

00:00:57.050 --> 00:00:58.920 align:middle line:90%
Earth is in great danger.

00:00:58.920 --> 00:01:00.840 align:middle line:90%
>>Ah!

00:01:00.840 --> 00:01:03.720 align:middle line:90%
>>Pew-pew.

00:01:03.720 --> 00:01:07.560 align:middle line:90%
>>[EVIL LAUGH]

00:01:07.560 --> 00:01:08.141 align:middle line:90%


00:01:08.141 --> 00:01:10.390 align:middle line:84%
>>GEORGE NOORY: Wow, well,
welcome to "Beyond Belief."

00:01:10.390 --> 00:01:11.380 align:middle line:10%
I'm George Noory.

00:01:11.380 --> 00:01:15.070 align:middle line:10%
And that was a clip from "A
Stranger at the Pentagon"

00:01:15.070 --> 00:01:17.540 align:middle line:10%
by Craig Campobasso,
who's the writer,

00:01:17.540 --> 00:01:21.280 align:middle line:10%
director, producer--
just about did it all.

00:01:21.280 --> 00:01:22.169 align:middle line:90%
That was a neat film!

00:01:22.169 --> 00:01:23.960 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAIG CAMPOBASSO:
Hey, thank you, George.

00:01:23.960 --> 00:01:24.170 align:middle line:90%
Thanks very much.

00:01:24.170 --> 00:01:25.110 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Welcome
to "Beyond Belief."

00:01:25.110 --> 00:01:26.776 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: I'm
very happy to be here.

00:01:26.776 --> 00:01:32.280 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: This project that you
undertook started how long ago.

00:01:32.280 --> 00:01:34.840 align:middle line:10%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Well, I
met Dr. Stranges in-- I

00:01:34.840 --> 00:01:37.790 align:middle line:10%
believe it was early 2002.

00:01:37.790 --> 00:01:39.190 align:middle line:10%
And we became friends.

00:01:39.190 --> 00:01:42.460 align:middle line:10%
And just over a
course of time, he

00:01:42.460 --> 00:01:44.930 align:middle line:10%
told me there were
many stops and starts

00:01:44.930 --> 00:01:46.480 align:middle line:10%
to get it made into a movie.

00:01:46.480 --> 00:01:49.650 align:middle line:10%
And somebody had called and
wanted to make it into a movie.

00:01:49.650 --> 00:01:52.235 align:middle line:84%
And he wanted me to go
with him to the meeting,

00:01:52.235 --> 00:01:54.360 align:middle line:84%
since I've been in the film
business my whole life.

00:01:54.360 --> 00:01:58.690 align:middle line:90%
So I went to the meeting.

00:01:58.690 --> 00:02:00.990 align:middle line:90%
It didn't turn out well.

00:02:00.990 --> 00:02:05.390 align:middle line:84%
And I had to sort of tell
Dr. Frank that he couldn't

00:02:05.390 --> 00:02:07.410 align:middle line:90%
get involved with this person.

00:02:07.410 --> 00:02:11.740 align:middle line:84%
And I just saw how
disappointed he was.

00:02:11.740 --> 00:02:14.810 align:middle line:84%
And so, that began the
journey with me just

00:02:14.810 --> 00:02:16.200 align:middle line:90%
sitting with him for years.

00:02:16.200 --> 00:02:19.220 align:middle line:84%
I said, just tell
me stories of you

00:02:19.220 --> 00:02:23.110 align:middle line:84%
with Valiant Thor and his
crew and all of everything

00:02:23.110 --> 00:02:24.050 align:middle line:90%
that's gone on.

00:02:24.050 --> 00:02:27.010 align:middle line:84%
Because the book is
vignettes of things

00:02:27.010 --> 00:02:28.490 align:middle line:84%
that happened
throughout the years.

00:02:28.490 --> 00:02:31.710 align:middle line:84%
So we had to have a
chunk of a story-line.

00:02:31.710 --> 00:02:38.430 align:middle line:84%
So we did that, worked on the
major script for several years

00:02:38.430 --> 00:02:43.470 align:middle line:84%
and, then, was going to
raised the money to do

00:02:43.470 --> 00:02:47.260 align:middle line:90%
the film privately, right?

00:02:47.260 --> 00:02:51.487 align:middle line:84%
And then, Dr. Frank passed
away in November of 2008.

00:02:51.487 --> 00:02:53.070 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Before you
could finish this.

00:02:53.070 --> 00:02:55.330 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Before we
could get the movie made.

00:02:55.330 --> 00:02:57.330 align:middle line:90%
The script was done.

00:02:57.330 --> 00:02:59.070 align:middle line:90%
So it was pretty devastating.

00:02:59.070 --> 00:03:02.110 align:middle line:84%
And then, a couple
years after that,

00:03:02.110 --> 00:03:05.290 align:middle line:84%
I worked on a film-- one
of the casting directors

00:03:05.290 --> 00:03:07.040 align:middle line:84%
on "Sky Captain and
the World of Tomorrow"

00:03:07.040 --> 00:03:11.130 align:middle line:84%
with Jude Law and Angelina
Jolie and another film

00:03:11.130 --> 00:03:13.580 align:middle line:84%
with the producer who
did the "Saw" movies.

00:03:13.580 --> 00:03:16.800 align:middle line:84%
Those movies were
independent movies.

00:03:16.800 --> 00:03:19.370 align:middle line:84%
They came about because
they made a short film.

00:03:19.370 --> 00:03:22.990 align:middle line:84%
And they used that as their
expensive sizzle reel,

00:03:22.990 --> 00:03:25.010 align:middle line:90%
to gain the private financing.

00:03:25.010 --> 00:03:27.240 align:middle line:84%
So both those films were
actually privately financed.

00:03:27.240 --> 00:03:27.948 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Perfect.

00:03:27.948 --> 00:03:31.120 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: So I decided,
I'm going to do a short film

00:03:31.120 --> 00:03:34.192 align:middle line:84%
and call in all the favors
from all of my friends

00:03:34.192 --> 00:03:35.900 align:middle line:84%
throughout all the
years in the business.

00:03:35.900 --> 00:03:39.390 align:middle line:84%
And we even had James Cameron's
visual effects coordinator

00:03:39.390 --> 00:03:39.980 align:middle line:90%
on board.

00:03:39.980 --> 00:03:41.800 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Yeah, talent
you just can't buy.

00:03:41.800 --> 00:03:42.966 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: You can't, no.

00:03:42.966 --> 00:03:46.040 align:middle line:84%
And all these people gave
of themselves freely.

00:03:46.040 --> 00:03:49.876 align:middle line:84%
And I always said, this
movie was made by the people,

00:03:49.876 --> 00:03:50.500 align:middle line:90%
for the people.

00:03:50.500 --> 00:03:52.210 align:middle line:84%
Because the people
wanted to see it.

00:03:52.210 --> 00:03:54.470 align:middle line:84%
Because people are the
ones that helped fund it.

00:03:54.470 --> 00:03:56.590 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: All based on the
work of Frank Stranges.

00:03:56.590 --> 00:03:57.340 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Yes.

00:03:57.340 --> 00:04:01.080 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Who I remember as a
kid, reading some of his works.

00:04:01.080 --> 00:04:03.900 align:middle line:90%
He was huge into the UFO field.

00:04:03.900 --> 00:04:04.650 align:middle line:90%
Huge.

00:04:04.650 --> 00:04:06.670 align:middle line:90%
And he loved it.

00:04:06.670 --> 00:04:10.980 align:middle line:84%
What an incredible story though,
"The Stranger at the Pentagon,"

00:04:10.980 --> 00:04:12.895 align:middle line:84%
about someone who comes
from another planet.

00:04:12.895 --> 00:04:15.920 align:middle line:90%


00:04:15.920 --> 00:04:17.529 align:middle line:90%
Was it a drama?

00:04:17.529 --> 00:04:19.730 align:middle line:90%
Or was it real?

00:04:19.730 --> 00:04:21.720 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Well, when
I sat with Dr. Frank

00:04:21.720 --> 00:04:23.800 align:middle line:84%
and talked to him-- I
read the book in the '80s.

00:04:23.800 --> 00:04:27.510 align:middle line:84%
And I sort of filed it
away and just thought, wow.

00:04:27.510 --> 00:04:30.020 align:middle line:84%
There's pictures of
this man, Valiant Thor,

00:04:30.020 --> 00:04:31.620 align:middle line:90%
his vice-commander, Donn.

00:04:31.620 --> 00:04:33.720 align:middle line:84%
And then, there's
another lady whose name

00:04:33.720 --> 00:04:35.500 align:middle line:90%
is Jill, who's a blond.

00:04:35.500 --> 00:04:38.440 align:middle line:84%
And I later found
out from Dr. Frank,

00:04:38.440 --> 00:04:40.990 align:middle line:84%
she's the wife of
Vice-Commander Zann.

00:04:40.990 --> 00:04:43.760 align:middle line:84%
And those pictures were taken
in Howard Menger's backyard

00:04:43.760 --> 00:04:45.820 align:middle line:84%
in High Bridge, New
Jersey, during the time

00:04:45.820 --> 00:04:46.820 align:middle line:90%
that Valiant Thor was--

00:04:46.820 --> 00:04:47.870 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And they look human.

00:04:47.870 --> 00:04:48.250 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Right.

00:04:48.250 --> 00:04:49.210 align:middle line:90%
They look human.

00:04:49.210 --> 00:04:52.870 align:middle line:84%
Actually, they're all
quite good looking.

00:04:52.870 --> 00:04:58.530 align:middle line:84%
And anyway, so a retired
Air Force photographer

00:04:58.530 --> 00:05:02.270 align:middle line:84%
and UFOlogist, August
Roberts, was there that day.

00:05:02.270 --> 00:05:03.910 align:middle line:84%
And he saw that
Valiant Thor didn't

00:05:03.910 --> 00:05:08.370 align:middle line:84%
have palm prints, fingerprints;
that he spoke to people

00:05:08.370 --> 00:05:14.320 align:middle line:84%
in different languages; and that
when he looked at him, he said,

00:05:14.320 --> 00:05:17.310 align:middle line:90%
he looked right through me.

00:05:17.310 --> 00:05:19.170 align:middle line:84%
And when he look
through me, he could

00:05:19.170 --> 00:05:21.669 align:middle line:84%
feel him reading his
entire soul history.

00:05:21.669 --> 00:05:22.210 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Wow.

00:05:22.210 --> 00:05:24.084 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: He said
it was beyond anything.

00:05:24.084 --> 00:05:27.850 align:middle line:84%
He said, you knew that
this man was not from here

00:05:27.850 --> 00:05:36.030 align:middle line:84%
and that he felt that he was
of the angelic class of beings.

00:05:36.030 --> 00:05:39.350 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I've been a UFO buff
all my life, all my life.

00:05:39.350 --> 00:05:43.030 align:middle line:84%
I know practically every
major UFO case that

00:05:43.030 --> 00:05:45.870 align:middle line:90%
has occurred on this planet.

00:05:45.870 --> 00:05:49.170 align:middle line:90%
And this one is mind boggling.

00:05:49.170 --> 00:05:52.430 align:middle line:84%
The fact that an
extraterrestrial would

00:05:52.430 --> 00:05:55.510 align:middle line:84%
come here, would try
to give us, really,

00:05:55.510 --> 00:05:58.420 align:middle line:90%
plans to build our future.

00:05:58.420 --> 00:06:00.450 align:middle line:90%
Not quite-- thank, God.

00:06:00.450 --> 00:06:03.900 align:middle line:84%
It's like the "Twilight
Zone" film, right?

00:06:03.900 --> 00:06:04.740 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Right.

00:06:04.740 --> 00:06:07.590 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It's not
a cookbook, right?

00:06:07.590 --> 00:06:09.425 align:middle line:90%
But just an amazing story.

00:06:09.425 --> 00:06:13.750 align:middle line:84%
And looking at that
picture of Valiant Thor--

00:06:13.750 --> 00:06:15.050 align:middle line:90%
good looking guy from--

00:06:15.050 --> 00:06:15.910 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: It's
chilling to actually--

00:06:15.910 --> 00:06:16.190 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It is chilling.

00:06:16.190 --> 00:06:18.920 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: --look at him,
if you study it as well.

00:06:18.920 --> 00:06:20.790 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What happened
to Valiant Thor?

00:06:20.790 --> 00:06:22.580 align:middle line:90%
Did he leave the planet?

00:06:22.580 --> 00:06:23.320 align:middle line:90%
Did he die?

00:06:23.320 --> 00:06:24.740 align:middle line:90%
Where is he now?

00:06:24.740 --> 00:06:27.000 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Well,
everything that I tell

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:28.560 align:middle line:90%
you is what Dr. Frank told me.

00:06:28.560 --> 00:06:31.470 align:middle line:84%
So I'm, I guess,
the spokesperson.

00:06:31.470 --> 00:06:32.970 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You're the
go-between, now.

00:06:32.970 --> 00:06:34.928 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: I'm the
go-between at this point,

00:06:34.928 --> 00:06:36.040 align:middle line:90%
since Dr. Frank is gone.

00:06:36.040 --> 00:06:41.790 align:middle line:90%
But he left on March 16, 1960.

00:06:41.790 --> 00:06:45.730 align:middle line:84%
And then, returned
on March 16, 1961.

00:06:45.730 --> 00:06:48.102 align:middle line:84%
And Dr. Frank said, has
been here ever since.

00:06:48.102 --> 00:06:49.060 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: He's here now.

00:06:49.060 --> 00:06:50.230 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: He's here now.

00:06:50.230 --> 00:06:54.680 align:middle line:84%
And he commands a
giant starship that is

00:06:54.680 --> 00:06:58.120 align:middle line:90%
14 miles long and 7 miles wide.

00:06:58.120 --> 00:07:01.030 align:middle line:84%
And that there is a
Victor Class fleet.

00:07:01.030 --> 00:07:04.280 align:middle line:84%
And his saucer is Victor
I. And there's Victor II,

00:07:04.280 --> 00:07:06.020 align:middle line:90%
Victor III, Victor IV.

00:07:06.020 --> 00:07:08.690 align:middle line:84%
These saucers are
300 feet in diameter.

00:07:08.690 --> 00:07:09.690 align:middle line:90%
They're double-deckered.

00:07:09.690 --> 00:07:11.360 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: We may have
seen some of them.

00:07:11.360 --> 00:07:12.110 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Yes.

00:07:12.110 --> 00:07:15.410 align:middle line:84%
And we do-- and I'm sure,
at some point in the show,

00:07:15.410 --> 00:07:18.180 align:middle line:84%
we're going to show the
blueprints to the Victor Class

00:07:18.180 --> 00:07:20.880 align:middle line:90%
saucers as well.

00:07:20.880 --> 00:07:24.650 align:middle line:84%
And they hold up
to 200 in the crew.

00:07:24.650 --> 00:07:27.080 align:middle line:84%
And there are over
100 of them stationed

00:07:27.080 --> 00:07:31.910 align:middle line:84%
in and around the Earth,
monitoring 287 locations.

00:07:31.910 --> 00:07:34.050 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Where are they from?

00:07:34.050 --> 00:07:37.070 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Well, they could
be from all over the universe

00:07:37.070 --> 00:07:38.430 align:middle line:90%
and other parts of the universe.

00:07:38.430 --> 00:07:42.430 align:middle line:84%
But Valiant Thor and his
immediate Vice-Commander crew

00:07:42.430 --> 00:07:44.960 align:middle line:90%
are from the interior of Venus.

00:07:44.960 --> 00:07:49.360 align:middle line:84%
And Dr. Frank explained that
Valiant Thor explained to him

00:07:49.360 --> 00:07:52.520 align:middle line:84%
that all of the planets
throughout our galaxy

00:07:52.520 --> 00:07:57.280 align:middle line:84%
are populated on the
inside and that they

00:07:57.280 --> 00:08:00.870 align:middle line:84%
have ways of
terracing the insides

00:08:00.870 --> 00:08:03.020 align:middle line:84%
and making them
like a spaceship.

00:08:03.020 --> 00:08:05.690 align:middle line:84%
They have ways of making
synchrotron skies.

00:08:05.690 --> 00:08:08.520 align:middle line:84%
So if you're looking
up into the sky,

00:08:08.520 --> 00:08:11.880 align:middle line:84%
you believe that you're
looking out into the real sky.

00:08:11.880 --> 00:08:15.360 align:middle line:84%
And they go from day
to night as well.

00:08:15.360 --> 00:08:17.980 align:middle line:84%
And that this is
also a way that they

00:08:17.980 --> 00:08:21.340 align:middle line:84%
can control the
temperature-- but not only

00:08:21.340 --> 00:08:26.170 align:middle line:84%
that-- the resignation fields
that keep theirselves young,

00:08:26.170 --> 00:08:27.760 align:middle line:90%
so that they don't age.

00:08:27.760 --> 00:08:30.430 align:middle line:84%
They stop aging
at about 30, even

00:08:30.430 --> 00:08:33.330 align:middle line:84%
though the ones that are
born of man and woman

00:08:33.330 --> 00:08:36.260 align:middle line:84%
can live up to
1,000, 2,000 years.

00:08:36.260 --> 00:08:39.329 align:middle line:84%
Created beings, such as
Valiant Thor, are immortal.

00:08:39.329 --> 00:08:41.450 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Isn't that
an amazing story?

00:08:41.450 --> 00:08:44.920 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Yes, and I've
been doing lots of shows

00:08:44.920 --> 00:08:49.130 align:middle line:84%
throughout my life,
casting science fiction

00:08:49.130 --> 00:08:50.800 align:middle line:90%
shows and all of that.

00:08:50.800 --> 00:08:54.990 align:middle line:84%
And this story, though,
is one that brings hope.

00:08:54.990 --> 00:08:58.750 align:middle line:84%
And people can't believe
it when they hear it,

00:08:58.750 --> 00:09:02.610 align:middle line:84%
that there are such
beings out there who

00:09:02.610 --> 00:09:06.870 align:middle line:84%
have this incredible
compassion for us

00:09:06.870 --> 00:09:09.950 align:middle line:84%
and that are here to help
assist, even though it

00:09:09.950 --> 00:09:13.110 align:middle line:90%
may be invisible to us knowing.

00:09:13.110 --> 00:09:17.180 align:middle line:84%
But it's starting to
break through the barriers

00:09:17.180 --> 00:09:18.270 align:middle line:90%
and the veil.

00:09:18.270 --> 00:09:20.150 align:middle line:84%
And bringing this
up, this short film

00:09:20.150 --> 00:09:23.750 align:middle line:84%
alone was never intended
for anybody to see.

00:09:23.750 --> 00:09:24.520 align:middle line:90%
The world wanted--

00:09:24.520 --> 00:09:25.570 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It's just
your sizzle reel.

00:09:25.570 --> 00:09:26.320 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: A
sizzle reel, yeah.

00:09:26.320 --> 00:09:27.611 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: For getting financing.

00:09:27.611 --> 00:09:29.340 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Everybody
wanted to see it.

00:09:29.340 --> 00:09:33.580 align:middle line:84%
They wanted to see
it so desperately.

00:09:33.580 --> 00:09:35.270 align:middle line:84%
So I made it
available for everyone

00:09:35.270 --> 00:09:37.240 align:middle line:84%
to see and travel
around with it.

00:09:37.240 --> 00:09:40.344 align:middle line:84%
And as you know, we've
won two film festivals--

00:09:40.344 --> 00:09:41.260 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yes, you have

00:09:41.260 --> 00:09:42.593 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: --with it as well.

00:09:42.593 --> 00:09:43.180 align:middle line:90%
Which is nice.

00:09:43.180 --> 00:09:45.890 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Wouldn't you
love to meet Valiant Thor.

00:09:45.890 --> 00:09:47.260 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: I would really
love to meet Valiant Thor.

00:09:47.260 --> 00:09:47.900 align:middle line:90%
And I know--

00:09:47.900 --> 00:09:49.310 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: What would you ask him?

00:09:49.310 --> 00:09:54.570 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Um, I have a
long laundry list of questions

00:09:54.570 --> 00:09:55.455 align:middle line:90%
that I would ask him.

00:09:55.455 --> 00:09:57.210 align:middle line:84%
But I think what
I would really do

00:09:57.210 --> 00:10:02.240 align:middle line:84%
first is I would
really like to just sit

00:10:02.240 --> 00:10:08.820 align:middle line:84%
with them and their energy and
just talk about regular things.

00:10:08.820 --> 00:10:11.340 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Tell me the
significance of Harley Byrd.

00:10:11.340 --> 00:10:13.190 align:middle line:84%
And any relation
to Admiral Byrd?

00:10:13.190 --> 00:10:14.020 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Yes.

00:10:14.020 --> 00:10:16.070 align:middle line:90%
He was his nephew.

00:10:16.070 --> 00:10:18.510 align:middle line:84%
I've recently obtained
a couple of documents

00:10:18.510 --> 00:10:20.660 align:middle line:90%
from the Byrd estate.

00:10:20.660 --> 00:10:25.000 align:middle line:84%
The first one is a letter
written by Admiral Richard Byrd

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:29.910 align:middle line:84%
to Rear Admiral Daniel Smith,
who was the Chief Naval

00:10:29.910 --> 00:10:32.501 align:middle line:84%
Operations Officer
over at the Pentagon

00:10:32.501 --> 00:10:33.750 align:middle line:90%
for the Department of Defense.

00:10:33.750 --> 00:10:34.360 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: CNO?

00:10:34.360 --> 00:10:35.151 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Yeah.

00:10:35.151 --> 00:10:39.500 align:middle line:84%
And he wrote a letter
to Harley at that time.

00:10:39.500 --> 00:10:42.160 align:middle line:90%
He was recently married in '56.

00:10:42.160 --> 00:10:44.180 align:middle line:90%
He had a baby on the way.

00:10:44.180 --> 00:10:46.650 align:middle line:90%
And he needed a real job.

00:10:46.650 --> 00:10:53.610 align:middle line:84%
So he was in the-- oh,
what do you call it?

00:10:53.610 --> 00:10:54.235 align:middle line:90%
The Guard.

00:10:54.235 --> 00:10:54.921 align:middle line:90%
The--

00:10:54.921 --> 00:10:55.670 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Reserves.

00:10:55.670 --> 00:10:58.360 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Yes, thank you.

00:10:58.360 --> 00:10:59.770 align:middle line:90%
So anyway, he wrote a letter.

00:10:59.770 --> 00:11:03.570 align:middle line:84%
And then, he started working
for the Department of Defense

00:11:03.570 --> 00:11:08.030 align:middle line:84%
in '57, which is at the time
that Valiant Thor was there.

00:11:08.030 --> 00:11:11.140 align:middle line:84%
And anyway, the other
document that I have

00:11:11.140 --> 00:11:14.030 align:middle line:84%
is his honorable
discharge papers,

00:11:14.030 --> 00:11:19.900 align:middle line:84%
which show that he was,
among many other titles,

00:11:19.900 --> 00:11:23.020 align:middle line:84%
special assignment
officer as well

00:11:23.020 --> 00:11:24.520 align:middle line:84%
there for the
Department of Defense.

00:11:24.520 --> 00:11:24.800 align:middle line:90%
So--

00:11:24.800 --> 00:11:27.075 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Did they put him in
charge of, like, Project Blue

00:11:27.075 --> 00:11:27.200 align:middle line:90%
Book.

00:11:27.200 --> 00:11:29.670 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: He was a part
of Project Blue Book, yes.

00:11:29.670 --> 00:11:35.320 align:middle line:84%
And so, he wrote the foreword
to "Stranger at the Pentagon,"

00:11:35.320 --> 00:11:38.832 align:middle line:84%
confirming, giving the case
file number, and everything.

00:11:38.832 --> 00:11:40.290 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So they
investigated this?

00:11:40.290 --> 00:11:41.080 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Yes.

00:11:41.080 --> 00:11:42.909 align:middle line:84%
Well, he was right
there at the Pentagon.

00:11:42.909 --> 00:11:43.950 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That is amazing.

00:11:43.950 --> 00:11:47.150 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Yeah, so
it's an amazing thing.

00:11:47.150 --> 00:11:52.590 align:middle line:84%
So there is that proof
there from Harley Byrd.

00:11:52.590 --> 00:11:57.640 align:middle line:84%
And by the way, Harley-- I found
out-- passed away, I think,

00:11:57.640 --> 00:11:59.592 align:middle line:84%
March 11, 2009, not
long after Dr. Frank.

00:11:59.592 --> 00:12:01.300 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Was he a
believer, do you think?

00:12:01.300 --> 00:12:01.520 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Yes.

00:12:01.520 --> 00:12:02.660 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: --in this entire story?

00:12:02.660 --> 00:12:03.950 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Yes, absolutely.

00:12:03.950 --> 00:12:06.710 align:middle line:84%
I actually think he
met Valiant Thor.

00:12:06.710 --> 00:12:08.855 align:middle line:84%
Because he was there
at the Pentagon.

00:12:08.855 --> 00:12:10.730 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: There was a
picture of Valiant Thor.

00:12:10.730 --> 00:12:11.200 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Yeah.

00:12:11.200 --> 00:12:13.700 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Were there any
pictures of him with Eisenhower?

00:12:13.700 --> 00:12:14.790 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: No,
not that I know of.

00:12:14.790 --> 00:12:16.290 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You didn't
see any of them.

00:12:16.290 --> 00:12:18.300 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: But
here's what I think.

00:12:18.300 --> 00:12:21.324 align:middle line:84%
There has to exist,
somewhere, photographs

00:12:21.324 --> 00:12:22.240 align:middle line:90%
of him and Eisenhower.

00:12:22.240 --> 00:12:22.980 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Oh my gosh.

00:12:22.980 --> 00:12:23.100 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:12:23.100 --> 00:12:23.520 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Somewhere.

00:12:23.520 --> 00:12:26.010 align:middle line:84%
I mean, wouldn't you have
taken a picture with him?

00:12:26.010 --> 00:12:26.960 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Many, many.

00:12:26.960 --> 00:12:29.890 align:middle line:84%
Now, when you say that
Valiant Thor is still here,

00:12:29.890 --> 00:12:32.020 align:middle line:90%
are you talking about up there?

00:12:32.020 --> 00:12:33.470 align:middle line:90%
Or physically on this planet?

00:12:33.470 --> 00:12:35.440 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Physically
on the planet.

00:12:35.440 --> 00:12:37.790 align:middle line:84%
His craft, like I said,
is called Victor 1.

00:12:37.790 --> 00:12:40.889 align:middle line:90%
And it's stationed at Lake Mead.

00:12:40.889 --> 00:12:42.430 align:middle line:84%
Actually, in the
book, it gives the--

00:12:42.430 --> 00:12:43.040 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: In the lake?

00:12:43.040 --> 00:12:44.290 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Not in the lake.

00:12:44.290 --> 00:12:46.700 align:middle line:90%
But it's more on dry land.

00:12:46.700 --> 00:12:52.300 align:middle line:84%
I actually went out there,
actually, on March 16 this year

00:12:52.300 --> 00:12:55.590 align:middle line:90%
and went to check out the site.

00:12:55.590 --> 00:12:58.340 align:middle line:84%
Because we can now do it
with GPS, because we had the

00:12:58.340 --> 00:12:59.340 align:middle line:90%
coordinates.

00:12:59.340 --> 00:13:01.920 align:middle line:90%
And it's just big open space.

00:13:01.920 --> 00:13:04.810 align:middle line:84%
And it's perfect for
taking off and landing

00:13:04.810 --> 00:13:06.650 align:middle line:90%
and all that kind of stuff.

00:13:06.650 --> 00:13:07.650 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Nobody sees it.

00:13:07.650 --> 00:13:08.858 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Nobody sees it.

00:13:08.858 --> 00:13:11.150 align:middle line:84%
Dr. Frank always talked
about a [? Verishield ?],

00:13:11.150 --> 00:13:12.790 align:middle line:90%
is what he called it.

00:13:12.790 --> 00:13:14.934 align:middle line:84%
When they would go pick
him up in Las Vegas

00:13:14.934 --> 00:13:17.350 align:middle line:84%
and, then, drive him to Lake
Mead-- because they had cars.

00:13:17.350 --> 00:13:18.420 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Vegas-- I love
the way that sounds.

00:13:18.420 --> 00:13:19.280 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: They do.

00:13:19.280 --> 00:13:19.780 align:middle line:90%
I know.

00:13:19.780 --> 00:13:21.424 align:middle line:90%
They did.

00:13:21.424 --> 00:13:22.451 align:middle line:90%
He said that--

00:13:22.451 --> 00:13:23.700 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: He sang with Sinatra.

00:13:23.700 --> 00:13:24.491 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Yeah.

00:13:24.491 --> 00:13:26.950 align:middle line:90%


00:13:26.950 --> 00:13:28.740 align:middle line:84%
--the [? Verishield ?]
just opens up.

00:13:28.740 --> 00:13:31.410 align:middle line:84%
They just drive right in
to the belly of the craft.

00:13:31.410 --> 00:13:31.540 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And it closes.

00:13:31.540 --> 00:13:32.860 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: And then,
it closes right up.

00:13:32.860 --> 00:13:34.590 align:middle line:84%
But if there were
people here, they

00:13:34.590 --> 00:13:38.120 align:middle line:84%
could even extend the
shield out this way,

00:13:38.120 --> 00:13:40.360 align:middle line:84%
so nobody even sees
the car coming in.

00:13:40.360 --> 00:13:43.260 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Why the interest, do
you think, in this country?

00:13:43.260 --> 00:13:45.610 align:middle line:90%
In this planet?

00:13:45.610 --> 00:13:50.820 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Well, because this
planet is dualistic in nature.

00:13:50.820 --> 00:13:56.460 align:middle line:84%
And from what I
understand, they're

00:13:56.460 --> 00:13:58.641 align:middle line:90%
all fully conscious beings.

00:13:58.641 --> 00:13:59.640 align:middle line:90%
I think, what do we use?

00:13:59.640 --> 00:14:01.007 align:middle line:90%
33 and 1/3 of our brain?

00:14:01.007 --> 00:14:01.590 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah.

00:14:01.590 --> 00:14:02.910 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: They're
at full capacity.

00:14:02.910 --> 00:14:03.750 align:middle line:90%
Imagine what that--

00:14:03.750 --> 00:14:04.130 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Some of us do.

00:14:04.130 --> 00:14:05.720 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Some
of us do, right.

00:14:05.720 --> 00:14:07.250 align:middle line:90%
But they're at full capacity.

00:14:07.250 --> 00:14:11.220 align:middle line:84%
And imagine what somebody
like his brain is

00:14:11.220 --> 00:14:13.150 align:middle line:90%
and what they can do.

00:14:13.150 --> 00:14:15.620 align:middle line:84%
So they're here for the
shifting of consciousness,

00:14:15.620 --> 00:14:19.820 align:middle line:84%
of moving at a duality, moving
the heart with the mind.

00:14:19.820 --> 00:14:24.890 align:middle line:84%
And so as this planet
raises up, it'll

00:14:24.890 --> 00:14:28.160 align:middle line:84%
again rejoin with
the universal society

00:14:28.160 --> 00:14:30.177 align:middle line:84%
that it's forgotten about
for a very long time.

00:14:30.177 --> 00:14:32.510 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I want to look at
some of the behind-the-scenes

00:14:32.510 --> 00:14:34.170 align:middle line:84%
of your movie "Stranger
at the Pentagon."

00:14:34.170 --> 00:14:34.440 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Sure.

00:14:34.440 --> 00:14:36.210 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Because this
is really fantastic.

00:14:36.210 --> 00:14:37.060 align:middle line:90%
Take a look at this.

00:14:37.060 --> 00:14:38.850 align:middle line:90%


00:14:38.850 --> 00:14:41.120 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Hi,
I'm Craig Campobasso,

00:14:41.120 --> 00:14:43.580 align:middle line:84%
screenwriter, producer, and
director of the short film

00:14:43.580 --> 00:14:45.340 align:middle line:90%
"Stranger at the Pentagon."

00:14:45.340 --> 00:14:47.350 align:middle line:84%
I'm sitting here in front
of this green-screen,

00:14:47.350 --> 00:14:50.710 align:middle line:84%
similar to the one that
we used on the sound stage

00:14:50.710 --> 00:14:53.790 align:middle line:84%
where we just finished
shooting our space drama,

00:14:53.790 --> 00:14:57.380 align:middle line:84%
inspired by a true story
about Valiant Thor, a created

00:14:57.380 --> 00:15:00.330 align:middle line:84%
being or an angel
in human form that

00:15:00.330 --> 00:15:02.240 align:middle line:84%
lived at the Pentagon
for three years

00:15:02.240 --> 00:15:04.650 align:middle line:84%
under the Eisenhower
administration.

00:15:04.650 --> 00:15:06.580 align:middle line:84%
Now, I'd like to
share some of our sets

00:15:06.580 --> 00:15:10.770 align:middle line:84%
with you-- the Joint
Chiefs of Staff,

00:15:10.770 --> 00:15:15.320 align:middle line:84%
the underground Washington
Basilica of the Evil Emperium,

00:15:15.320 --> 00:15:19.910 align:middle line:84%
the interrogation
room, the Oval Office.

00:15:19.910 --> 00:15:22.480 align:middle line:90%
Next up, custom design.

00:15:22.480 --> 00:15:28.560 align:middle line:84%
This is Valiant Thor's uniform;
the Vice-Commanders' uniforms;

00:15:28.560 --> 00:15:33.420 align:middle line:84%
Uniah, created being of
Melchizedek's uniform.

00:15:33.420 --> 00:15:37.460 align:middle line:84%
And this is Uniah's
associate, Yeo's uniform.

00:15:37.460 --> 00:15:40.021 align:middle line:84%
These are also the uniforms
of the galactic civilians.

00:15:40.021 --> 00:15:40.520 align:middle line:90%


00:15:40.520 --> 00:15:43.000 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Craig, that was
fun behind the scenes.

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:44.910 align:middle line:84%
But you can only
imagine what this

00:15:44.910 --> 00:15:49.365 align:middle line:84%
was really like, many years ago,
when this episode apparently

00:15:49.365 --> 00:15:49.865 align:middle line:90%
happened.

00:15:49.865 --> 00:15:50.170 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Yes.

00:15:50.170 --> 00:15:51.599 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It's just
mind-boggling.

00:15:51.599 --> 00:15:52.390 align:middle line:10%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Yeah.

00:15:52.390 --> 00:15:54.870 align:middle line:10%
And that's why I can't wait
to make the big giant feature

00:15:54.870 --> 00:15:55.370 align:middle line:10%
film.

00:15:55.370 --> 00:15:57.161 align:middle line:10%
Because we're going to
be on that starship.

00:15:57.161 --> 00:15:58.960 align:middle line:84%
We're going to be in
Victor I. And we're

00:15:58.960 --> 00:16:02.050 align:middle line:84%
going to see things that
we've never seen before.

00:16:02.050 --> 00:16:05.260 align:middle line:84%
This is just like
a little appetizer.

00:16:05.260 --> 00:16:08.620 align:middle line:84%
And imagine what we can do when
we really have a CGI budget

00:16:08.620 --> 00:16:12.060 align:middle line:84%
and can hire somebody
like George Lucas's ILM.

00:16:12.060 --> 00:16:14.185 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Who would play
the part of Valiant Thor?

00:16:14.185 --> 00:16:16.310 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Do you know
who I really really like?

00:16:16.310 --> 00:16:18.220 align:middle line:90%
Is Lee Pace.

00:16:18.220 --> 00:16:22.920 align:middle line:84%
Lee Pace starred in
"Guardians of the Galaxy."

00:16:22.920 --> 00:16:27.690 align:middle line:84%
He was in all the hobbit
movies and, I think,

00:16:27.690 --> 00:16:29.600 align:middle line:84%
"Pushing Daisies,"
the TV series.

00:16:29.600 --> 00:16:32.310 align:middle line:84%
He looks very similar
to Valiant Thor.

00:16:32.310 --> 00:16:33.500 align:middle line:90%
And he has that presence.

00:16:33.500 --> 00:16:35.390 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Well, you're
a casting director.

00:16:35.390 --> 00:16:36.389 align:middle line:90%
You know what to do.

00:16:36.389 --> 00:16:37.180 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: I do.

00:16:37.180 --> 00:16:37.780 align:middle line:90%
I do.

00:16:37.780 --> 00:16:41.150 align:middle line:84%
And Eileen Davidson, who played
his wife in the short film,

00:16:41.150 --> 00:16:44.260 align:middle line:84%
will be back and play her
in the feature film as well.

00:16:44.260 --> 00:16:47.920 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Do you
think, with this movie

00:16:47.920 --> 00:16:52.690 align:middle line:84%
and with this sizzle reel and if
it gets out to the big screen,

00:16:52.690 --> 00:16:58.080 align:middle line:84%
the real Valiant Thor will know
about it and will come down?

00:16:58.080 --> 00:17:00.390 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Well,
Dr. Frank said,

00:17:00.390 --> 00:17:03.440 align:middle line:84%
every time we were together
that they filmed us.

00:17:03.440 --> 00:17:05.410 align:middle line:90%
And they would store it.

00:17:05.410 --> 00:17:08.200 align:middle line:84%
And then, when they had
time or if they were eating,

00:17:08.200 --> 00:17:10.160 align:middle line:90%
they would actually watch it.

00:17:10.160 --> 00:17:12.940 align:middle line:84%
And so, I think that
everything is recorded

00:17:12.940 --> 00:17:16.819 align:middle line:84%
and that they look and see
how everything is coming out.

00:17:16.819 --> 00:17:19.359 align:middle line:84%
And I do hope that
someday he'll come down.

00:17:19.359 --> 00:17:21.640 align:middle line:84%
Hopefully, you'll get to
interview him, George.

00:17:21.640 --> 00:17:22.800 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I would love to
interview him on "Coast

00:17:22.800 --> 00:17:23.119 align:middle line:90%
to Coast"--

00:17:23.119 --> 00:17:23.785 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Would that
be the most awesome thing?

00:17:23.785 --> 00:17:25.180 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: --and "Beyond Belief."

00:17:25.180 --> 00:17:26.180 align:middle line:90%
That would be something.

00:17:26.180 --> 00:17:28.480 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Yeah, that
would be beyond belief for me.

00:17:28.480 --> 00:17:30.040 align:middle line:90%
That would be so cool, so cool.

00:17:30.040 --> 00:17:33.260 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I wonder if we
would be able to determine

00:17:33.260 --> 00:17:38.470 align:middle line:84%
if this guy was truly an
extraterrestrial or some kind

00:17:38.470 --> 00:17:39.127 align:middle line:90%
of good actor.

00:17:39.127 --> 00:17:41.710 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: No, we would know
he was because he doesn't have

00:17:41.710 --> 00:17:43.270 align:middle line:84%
a belly-button and
he doesn't have

00:17:43.270 --> 00:17:45.110 align:middle line:90%
fingerprints or palm-prints.

00:17:45.110 --> 00:17:47.560 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Would I ask you to
see if he has a belly-button?

00:17:47.560 --> 00:17:49.130 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Of course, yeah.

00:17:49.130 --> 00:17:50.680 align:middle line:90%
He would show that.

00:17:50.680 --> 00:17:51.560 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, absolutely.

00:17:51.560 --> 00:17:53.289 align:middle line:84%
And he would look
exactly the way

00:17:53.289 --> 00:17:54.580 align:middle line:90%
he looked from the photographs.

00:17:54.580 --> 00:17:55.570 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: He would
not have changed.

00:17:55.570 --> 00:17:56.630 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: He would
not have changed.

00:17:56.630 --> 00:17:58.520 align:middle line:84%
None of them have
changed one bit, no.

00:17:58.520 --> 00:18:02.564 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What was the most
fascinating point for you?

00:18:02.564 --> 00:18:04.230 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: The
most fascinating point

00:18:04.230 --> 00:18:08.270 align:middle line:84%
was learning more about
the story from Dr. Frank.

00:18:08.270 --> 00:18:13.320 align:middle line:84%
But when I was writing
it, the experience

00:18:13.320 --> 00:18:15.610 align:middle line:84%
that they gave me was, each
and every one of them--

00:18:15.610 --> 00:18:18.470 align:middle line:84%
including Valiant Thor--
put their feeling body

00:18:18.470 --> 00:18:19.479 align:middle line:90%
inside my body.

00:18:19.479 --> 00:18:20.770 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: What an amazing story.

00:18:20.770 --> 00:18:23.170 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: It was beyond
anything I've ever experienced.

00:18:23.170 --> 00:18:23.840 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It's beyond belief.

00:18:23.840 --> 00:18:25.215 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: It's
beyond belief.

00:18:25.215 --> 00:18:27.270 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How long have
you been in Hollywood now?

00:18:27.270 --> 00:18:30.350 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: I
started when I was 15.

00:18:30.350 --> 00:18:31.160 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Wow!

00:18:31.160 --> 00:18:34.080 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: I did
commercials and some bit parts

00:18:34.080 --> 00:18:38.480 align:middle line:84%
in movies and TV, transitioned
into a company called

00:18:38.480 --> 00:18:39.450 align:middle line:90%
Kaleidoscope Films.

00:18:39.450 --> 00:18:43.000 align:middle line:84%
I made teasers and
trailers for movies.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:44.970 align:middle line:84%
And then, I
transitioned from there,

00:18:44.970 --> 00:18:49.710 align:middle line:84%
going to Universal Studios and
worked for Dino de Laurentiis,

00:18:49.710 --> 00:18:52.300 align:middle line:84%
Raffaella de Laurentiis,
and David Lynch, who

00:18:52.300 --> 00:18:53.655 align:middle line:90%
were making "Dune."

00:18:53.655 --> 00:18:54.530 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Great movie.

00:18:54.530 --> 00:18:55.613 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Great movie.

00:18:55.613 --> 00:18:59.450 align:middle line:84%
And so, that's where I
learned all about filmmaking.

00:18:59.450 --> 00:19:02.500 align:middle line:84%
I worked on that film
from beginning conception

00:19:02.500 --> 00:19:03.570 align:middle line:90%
all the way to the end.

00:19:03.570 --> 00:19:05.675 align:middle line:84%
And that was a
four year journey.

00:19:05.675 --> 00:19:06.550 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: The "spice."

00:19:06.550 --> 00:19:08.680 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Yeah, the
"spice," the "melange."

00:19:08.680 --> 00:19:10.990 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Why was the
spice so important?

00:19:10.990 --> 00:19:12.880 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Well,
the spice was important

00:19:12.880 --> 00:19:16.720 align:middle line:84%
because it actually accelerated
consciousness, right?

00:19:16.720 --> 00:19:20.760 align:middle line:84%
And it's what created the
superbeing Paul Muad'dib.

00:19:20.760 --> 00:19:22.080 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Everybody wanted it.

00:19:22.080 --> 00:19:24.030 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Yeah.

00:19:24.030 --> 00:19:26.677 align:middle line:84%
And it was just an
amazing journey.

00:19:26.677 --> 00:19:28.760 align:middle line:84%
A lot of people don't know
a lot of the backstory.

00:19:28.760 --> 00:19:32.850 align:middle line:84%
But Val Kilmer was almost
playing Paul Muad'dib up until

00:19:32.850 --> 00:19:35.070 align:middle line:90%
Kyle McLaughlin was found.

00:19:35.070 --> 00:19:38.160 align:middle line:84%
Michael Biehn actually
screen-tested.

00:19:38.160 --> 00:19:40.716 align:middle line:84%
Kevin Costner
screen-tested as well.

00:19:40.716 --> 00:19:41.840 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It's a cult movie.

00:19:41.840 --> 00:19:43.173 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: It's a cult movie.

00:19:43.173 --> 00:19:45.210 align:middle line:84%
And David Lynch is
just so brilliant.

00:19:45.210 --> 00:19:49.630 align:middle line:84%
And it was such a joy to
work with and learn from him.

00:19:49.630 --> 00:19:54.780 align:middle line:84%
The movie today-- he wanted to
do a long version of the film

00:19:54.780 --> 00:19:57.080 align:middle line:90%
and asked Universal to wait.

00:19:57.080 --> 00:19:58.600 align:middle line:90%
And they said, no.

00:19:58.600 --> 00:20:00.650 align:middle line:84%
So Universal went and
cut a long version.

00:20:00.650 --> 00:20:02.210 align:middle line:84%
And David said,
take my name off.

00:20:02.210 --> 00:20:04.210 align:middle line:84%
So that version
you see, directed

00:20:04.210 --> 00:20:07.850 align:middle line:84%
by Alan Smithee, which is the
name the Director Guild uses

00:20:07.850 --> 00:20:10.020 align:middle line:84%
when a director wants
their name off a picture.

00:20:10.020 --> 00:20:12.230 align:middle line:84%
And I was just so
sad that David wasn't

00:20:12.230 --> 00:20:13.679 align:middle line:90%
unable to fulfill that dream.

00:20:13.679 --> 00:20:15.220 align:middle line:84%
Because that would've
been incredible

00:20:15.220 --> 00:20:16.555 align:middle line:90%
for us to see his whole vision.

00:20:16.555 --> 00:20:17.680 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sure.

00:20:17.680 --> 00:20:20.510 align:middle line:84%
We have seen an
evolution in Hollywood

00:20:20.510 --> 00:20:25.030 align:middle line:84%
with the stories on UFOs
and extraterrestrials.

00:20:25.030 --> 00:20:28.310 align:middle line:84%
And I'm kind of glad
you're bringing back yours

00:20:28.310 --> 00:20:31.650 align:middle line:84%
to something that has
some reality to it.

00:20:31.650 --> 00:20:32.410 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Yes.

00:20:32.410 --> 00:20:34.493 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: But Spielberg did
a great job with, like,

00:20:34.493 --> 00:20:36.390 align:middle line:84%
"Close Encounters
of the Third Kind,"

00:20:36.390 --> 00:20:39.656 align:middle line:90%
with "ET, the Extraterrestrial."

00:20:39.656 --> 00:20:43.080 align:middle line:84%
And there have been a lot
of other films in Hollywood

00:20:43.080 --> 00:20:46.300 align:middle line:84%
about good aliens
and bad aliens.

00:20:46.300 --> 00:20:47.450 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Bad aliens.

00:20:47.450 --> 00:20:52.480 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And we go back to Rod
Serling with "To Serve Man."

00:20:52.480 --> 00:20:53.054 align:middle line:90%
Come back!

00:20:53.054 --> 00:20:53.720 align:middle line:90%
It's a cookbook.

00:20:53.720 --> 00:20:54.470 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: It's a cookbook.

00:20:54.470 --> 00:20:54.760 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:20:54.760 --> 00:20:56.301 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: One of my
favorites as well.

00:20:56.301 --> 00:20:58.340 align:middle line:84%
But what are some of
your favorite movies

00:20:58.340 --> 00:20:59.810 align:middle line:84%
that are out there
in that genre.

00:20:59.810 --> 00:21:01.268 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Well,
in that genre--

00:21:01.268 --> 00:21:03.570 align:middle line:84%
the positive ones--
right at the top

00:21:03.570 --> 00:21:07.380 align:middle line:84%
of the list are "Contact,"
of course, "The Day the Earth

00:21:07.380 --> 00:21:08.040 align:middle line:90%
Stood Still."

00:21:08.040 --> 00:21:09.250 align:middle line:90%
I mean, it's still just--

00:21:09.250 --> 00:21:09.890 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: The original one.

00:21:09.890 --> 00:21:11.260 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: --such a classic.

00:21:11.260 --> 00:21:15.770 align:middle line:84%
And over the past few
years, I became friends

00:21:15.770 --> 00:21:20.360 align:middle line:84%
with Major George Filer, who
was working at the Pentagon

00:21:20.360 --> 00:21:22.505 align:middle line:90%
around '62, '63.

00:21:22.505 --> 00:21:24.380 align:middle line:84%
And he had heard of
Valiant Thor being there.

00:21:24.380 --> 00:21:25.430 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: He's big into UFOs.

00:21:25.430 --> 00:21:25.870 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Yeah.

00:21:25.870 --> 00:21:27.600 align:middle line:84%
He had heard of Valiant
Thor being there.

00:21:27.600 --> 00:21:31.650 align:middle line:84%
But he also told me that,
during that time period,

00:21:31.650 --> 00:21:34.787 align:middle line:84%
he was on an airplane and he
sat next to Michael Rennie--

00:21:34.787 --> 00:21:35.370 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Oooh!

00:21:35.370 --> 00:21:35.970 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Who played--

00:21:35.970 --> 00:21:37.320 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: He played the part.

00:21:37.320 --> 00:21:40.480 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: He
played the part, right?

00:21:40.480 --> 00:21:44.160 align:middle line:84%
And Michael Rennie told
him that the US government

00:21:44.160 --> 00:21:46.454 align:middle line:90%
funded that film to see--

00:21:46.454 --> 00:21:47.120 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Really?

00:21:47.120 --> 00:21:50.690 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Yeah-- to see what
the reaction of America would

00:21:50.690 --> 00:21:51.190 align:middle line:90%
be--

00:21:51.190 --> 00:21:52.180 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: That's
an amazing story.

00:21:52.180 --> 00:21:53.763 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: --to
an extraterrestrial

00:21:53.763 --> 00:21:56.180 align:middle line:90%
coming to the planet.

00:21:56.180 --> 00:21:58.950 align:middle line:84%
So I never would've
thought of that.

00:21:58.950 --> 00:22:02.150 align:middle line:84%
But I just thought, wow,
what an interesting thing.

00:22:02.150 --> 00:22:04.650 align:middle line:84%
And maybe they did that because
of "The War of the Worlds"--

00:22:04.650 --> 00:22:05.370 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That could be.

00:22:05.370 --> 00:22:06.080 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: The Orson Welles--

00:22:06.080 --> 00:22:06.760 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And the panic.

00:22:06.760 --> 00:22:08.301 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: --thing,
and the panic.

00:22:08.301 --> 00:22:11.380 align:middle line:84%
And maybe, they were just
gauging, is the world

00:22:11.380 --> 00:22:13.446 align:middle line:90%
ready to hear about this?

00:22:13.446 --> 00:22:15.070 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You mentioned
"Contact" as one

00:22:15.070 --> 00:22:16.550 align:middle line:84%
of your favorite
good alien movies.

00:22:16.550 --> 00:22:17.300 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Yes.

00:22:17.300 --> 00:22:18.440 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Let's take
a quick look at that.

00:22:18.440 --> 00:22:18.940 align:middle line:90%


00:22:18.940 --> 00:22:20.416 align:middle line:90%
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC]

00:22:20.416 --> 00:22:22.886 align:middle line:90%
>>Mark my mark.

00:22:22.886 --> 00:22:25.850 align:middle line:90%
10, 9--

00:22:25.850 --> 00:22:26.838 align:middle line:90%
>>Now, the transfer.

00:22:26.838 --> 00:22:29.802 align:middle line:90%
>>--8, 7--

00:22:29.802 --> 00:22:30.790 align:middle line:90%
>>On release.

00:22:30.790 --> 00:22:37.706 align:middle line:90%
>>--6, 5, 4, 3, 2--

00:22:37.706 --> 00:22:39.188 align:middle line:90%
>>I'm OK to go.

00:22:39.188 --> 00:22:42.646 align:middle line:90%


00:22:42.646 --> 00:22:45.116 align:middle line:90%
Oh, god!

00:22:45.116 --> 00:22:46.592 align:middle line:90%
Ah!

00:22:46.592 --> 00:22:47.092 align:middle line:90%
Ahh!

00:22:47.092 --> 00:22:48.300 align:middle line:90%


00:22:48.300 --> 00:22:50.050 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: That's one
of my favorite movies.

00:22:50.050 --> 00:22:52.740 align:middle line:84%
I just love the fact
that, toward the end,

00:22:52.740 --> 00:22:57.070 align:middle line:84%
the extraterrestrial who
creates the image of Ellie's

00:22:57.070 --> 00:23:00.850 align:middle line:84%
father and talks to her about
what they're looking for

00:23:00.850 --> 00:23:04.060 align:middle line:84%
and stuff-- and the message
I got from that, Craig--

00:23:04.060 --> 00:23:07.157 align:middle line:84%
was that they're
looking for God too.

00:23:07.157 --> 00:23:07.990 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Right.

00:23:07.990 --> 00:23:09.440 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: They can't find it.

00:23:09.440 --> 00:23:11.110 align:middle line:90%
They don't know what it is.

00:23:11.110 --> 00:23:12.900 align:middle line:90%
But they know it's out there.

00:23:12.900 --> 00:23:15.450 align:middle line:84%
And they're searching
for it, just like we are.

00:23:15.450 --> 00:23:17.930 align:middle line:84%
And it's almost
like a camaraderie,

00:23:17.930 --> 00:23:20.860 align:middle line:84%
a grouping of
people and entities,

00:23:20.860 --> 00:23:21.944 align:middle line:90%
to try to get that answer.

00:23:21.944 --> 00:23:23.318 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: To
get that answer.

00:23:23.318 --> 00:23:25.520 align:middle line:84%
And I think everybody's
searching for that answer.

00:23:25.520 --> 00:23:28.540 align:middle line:84%
And I think, in the
final, everybody

00:23:28.540 --> 00:23:32.000 align:middle line:90%
realizes that we're all God.

00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:33.460 align:middle line:90%
Everybody is God.

00:23:33.460 --> 00:23:35.540 align:middle line:84%
We're all at just
different levels

00:23:35.540 --> 00:23:38.310 align:middle line:84%
of learning and
combining and mixing.

00:23:38.310 --> 00:23:40.540 align:middle line:84%
And imagine, when
a planet like Earth

00:23:40.540 --> 00:23:44.480 align:middle line:84%
becomes a part of universal
society, what things we would

00:23:44.480 --> 00:23:46.915 align:middle line:84%
be learning from other
planetary spheres,

00:23:46.915 --> 00:23:48.665 align:middle line:84%
just like we learned
from other countries.

00:23:48.665 --> 00:23:49.100 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sure.

00:23:49.100 --> 00:23:50.683 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: And
that's mind-blowing.

00:23:50.683 --> 00:23:53.190 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Do you think there
are good extraterrestrials

00:23:53.190 --> 00:23:54.050 align:middle line:90%
and bad ones?

00:23:54.050 --> 00:23:55.280 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Yeah, I do.

00:23:55.280 --> 00:23:56.457 align:middle line:90%
I do.

00:23:56.457 --> 00:23:58.290 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You would think
in a great universe

00:23:58.290 --> 00:24:02.375 align:middle line:84%
that, if you reached a certain
plateau, you'd become good.

00:24:02.375 --> 00:24:04.000 align:middle line:84%
But that's not the
case, I don't think.

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:04.833 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Right.

00:24:04.833 --> 00:24:08.310 align:middle line:84%
Well, I often
wondered, would we be

00:24:08.310 --> 00:24:11.210 align:middle line:84%
bad extraterrestrials to
the good extraterrestrial

00:24:11.210 --> 00:24:11.950 align:middle line:90%
out there?

00:24:11.950 --> 00:24:15.500 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Tell me about the
movie "Flight of the Navigator."

00:24:15.500 --> 00:24:16.620 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Well, wow.

00:24:16.620 --> 00:24:17.772 align:middle line:90%
Let's see.

00:24:17.772 --> 00:24:19.980 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: That has to do with
time-travel, doesn't it?

00:24:19.980 --> 00:24:21.980 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: That does
have to do with time-travel.

00:24:21.980 --> 00:24:22.590 align:middle line:90%
And--

00:24:22.590 --> 00:24:23.790 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Well, let's
look at a clip.

00:24:23.790 --> 00:24:24.170 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPOBASSO: Yeah,
let's look at a clip.

00:24:24.170 --> 00:24:24.670 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Then we'll
talk about it.

00:24:24.670 --> 00:24:25.140 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPOBASSO: All right.

00:24:25.140 --> 00:24:25.640 align:middle line:90%
Good.

